Political Sophistication: item-response modeling with mixed data types

As part of a survey of French public opinion (see Grunberg, Mayer and Sniderman 2002), 2,148 respondents were administered a series of 19 items assessing their knowledge of political leaders, political institutions, constitutional provisions, and the policies of the political parties.   Each response is coded "correct" (1) or "incorrect" (0), and is modeled via a two-parameter item-response model, with a logistic link function; each respondent's level of political sophistication is the latent trait.

In addition, at the end of the thirty minute phone interview, the interviewer assigned a score for each respondent's level of political information (based on their impressions of the respondents formed over the course of the entire interview) on a zero to twenty scale. These responses are modeled via a linear regression, with each respondent's latent trait appearing as an unobserved predictor, and an intercept specific to each interviewer (modeled hierarchically in the code below). To uniquely orient the latent trait (higher values corresponding to more political sophistcation),  the interviewer ratings are constrained to positively discriminate with respect to the latent trait (see the constraint on the prior for gamma).

Reference: G?rard Grunberg, Nonna Mayer and Paul M. Sniderman (eds.), Democracy Under Strain (La democratie a l'epreuve: une nouvelle approche de l?opinion des Francais). 2002. Presses de Sciences Po: Paris.

$y_{i,j}$ are binary responsese to political information questions for respondant $i$ to question $j$.
$$
\begin{aligned}[t]
y_{i,j} &\sim \mathsf{Bernoulli}(\mathsf{Logit}^{-1}(\beta_j \xi_i - \alpha_j))
\end{aligned}
$$
Additionally, each interviewer assigned an overall knowledge score, $z_i$.
$$
\begin{aligned}[t]
z_i &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(\theta_i, \sigma^2)
\end{aligned}
$$
The interviewer score is modeled as a linear function of a the latent score of the respondent ($\xi_i$) and an interviewer specific random effect,
$$
\begin{aligned}[t]
\theta_i &= \gamma \xi_i + \nu(\mathtt{interiewer}_i) \\
\nu_m &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, \tau)
\end{aligned}
$$
Priors
$$
\begin{aligned}[t]
\xi_m &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, 1) \\
\tau &\sim \mathsf{HalfCauchy}(0, 5 s_{z} ) \\
\sigma &\sim \mathsf{HalfCauchy}(0, 5 s_{z} ) \\
\delta &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, 10 s_{z} ) \\
\beta_k &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, 2.5) \\
\alpha_k &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, 10) \\
\gamma &\sim \mathsf{HalfNormal}(0, 2.5 s_z)
\end{aligned}
$$

model{
	for (i in 1:2148){          ## loop over respondents
		for (j in 1:19){          ## loop over 19 binary responses
			y[i,j] ~ dbern(p[i,j]);
			logit(p[i,j]) <- beta[j,1]*x[i] - beta[j,2];  ## 2-parameter IRT
		}

	  ## interviewer ratings
		theta[i] <- gamma*x[i] + nu[id[i]];  ## linear model
		y[i,20] ~ dnorm(theta[i],tau);       ## normal regression model
	}

	## hierarchical structure, interviewer effects
	for(i in 1:27){
		nu[i] ~ dnorm(nu.bar, tau.nu)
	}
	nu.bar ~ dnorm(0.0, .001)	## prior, mean of interviewer effects dist

	## priors for precisions
	tau ~ dgamma(.01,.01);
	tau.nu ~ dgamma(.01,.01);

	## prior distributions
	for (i in 1:2148){
		x[i] ~ dnorm(0.0, 1.0);              ## prior for latent trait
	}

	## priors, discrimination parameters
	for (j in 1:19){
	  beta[j,1] ~ dnorm(0.0, 0.04);
		beta[j,2] ~ dnorm(0.0, 0.04);
	}
	## prior interviewer rating slope
	gamma ~ dnorm(0.0, .04)I(0,)

}
